VALUES ('bc9bbfc7-9c30-4569-9066-ea18e5add989', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical and precise word or phrase?', 'In archaeology, the standard view holds that early practitioners merely refined an inherited method; the more careful reading—one that attends to a qualification buried in a subordinate clause—suggests instead that they sought to qualify the method''s reach, bounding rather than extending it. Granting the surface impression of growth, the evidence nonetheless shows the practitioners working to qualify the very ambitions their successors would later celebrate, a restraint that the triumphalist chronology, attentive only to outcomes, cannot register.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"The word \"qualify,\" in its ordinary sense, means to detain or seize. This sense does not fit because nothing in the clause involves seizure or capture —given the dependency the text declines to name.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Collocation Decoy] Grounded in passage language but fails on a specific qualifier in its second sentence."},{"id":"B","text":"The word \"qualify,\" in a looser sense, means to encourage or advance. This sense does not fit because it reverses the restraint the qualifier establishes —given the dependency the text declines to name.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Over-Extrapolation] Grounded in passage language but fails on a specific qualifier in its second sentence."},{"id":"C","text":"The word \"qualify,\" in its specialized sense, means to limit or restrict. This sense fits because the clause opposes restraint to the successors'' ambitions —given the dependency the text declines to name.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: its second sentence is the only one that satisfies the discriminating condition."},{"id":"D","text":"The word \"qualify,\" in a connotative sense, means to celebrate openly. This sense does not fit because the passage''s tone is analytic, not celebratory —given the dependency the text declines to name.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Reverse Trap] Grounded in passage language but fails on a specific qualifier in its second sentence."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Logical Reconstruction:
Step 1: Identify the contrast: surface growth versus a buried qualification signalling restraint.
Step 2: Suppress the common senses of the word that collocate with the topic of progress.
Step 3: Select the rare sense that completes the restraint–ambition opposition precisely.
Step 4: Only "to limit or restrict" satisfies the syntactic position of the blank.

Key Explanation: Choice C is the only option whose second sentence survives the discriminating step above; the others are grounded in real passage language but fail a specific qualifier.

Distractor Analysis:
- Choice A [Collocation Decoy]: a 720–740 student is drawn to its accurate first sentence, but its second sentence imports a relationship the passage withholds — exactly the habit this trap exploits.
- Choice B [Over-Extrapolation]: a 720–740 student is drawn to its accurate first sentence, but its second sentence satisfies only part of the stated condition — exactly the habit this trap exploits.
