VALUES ('dd1ba2f7-8a62-4638-9d62-98e07396ff70', 'Which choice completes the text with the most logical transition?', 'That the method succeeded in the metropolitan laboratories, where funding and instruments were never scarce, is a fact the standard history of archaeology reports without qualification. ______ the provincial workshops, lacking those advantages yet reporting comparable results, expose a confound—patronage, not technique—that the celebratory account, fixed on outcomes, quietly omits.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"Owing precisely to this fact,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Reciprocal Error] A defensible misreading encodes a different relationship than the passage''s rhetorical direction."},{"id":"B","text":"Adding further to this point,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Over-Extrapolation] A defensible misreading encodes a different relationship than the passage''s rhetorical direction."},{"id":"C","text":"Despite these apparent surface similarities,","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: the five-word phrase encodes the contrast relationship the two nested sentences require."},{"id":"D","text":"As a direct logical result,","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Reciprocal Error] A defensible misreading encodes a different relationship than the passage''s rhetorical direction."}]'::jsonb, 'C', 'Logical Reconstruction:
Step 1: Parse the dense first sentence: success under favorable conditions.
Step 2: Parse the second: comparable success without those conditions.
Step 3: The relationship is a contrastive reframing, not addition or cause.
Step 4: Only the five-word phrase encoding that contrast fits.

Key Explanation: Choice C is the only option whose second sentence survives the discriminating step above; the others are grounded in real passage language but fail a specific qualifier.

Distractor Analysis:
- Choice A [Reciprocal Error]: a 720–740 student is drawn to its accurate first sentence, but its second sentence imports a relationship the passage withholds — exactly the habit this trap exploits.
- Choice B [Over-Extrapolation]: a 720–740 student is drawn to its accurate first sentence, but its second sentence satisfies only part of the stated condition — exactly the habit this trap exploits.
- Choice D [Rhetorical Misclassification]: a 720–740 student is drawn to its accurate first sentence, but its second sentence extends beyond the passage''s qualifiers — exactly the habit this trap exploits.

Difficulty Justification: This item is Challenge-tier because of five-word transition disambiguation at a fine-grained rhetorical sub-category single words cannot encode.

